{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"deb7f294-871e-4ca7-9a24-6c78c9837498","content":"This is a TUnit project (MTP-native). TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` syntax, not VSTest `--filter`. The command is:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nTUnit projects are built as executables (`OutputType: Exe`) and use Microsoft.Testing.Platform directly, so `dotnet run` with `--treenode-filter` is the standard way to filter by class. The glob pattern `/**/SmsNotificationTests/**` matches all tests under that class node.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7a4f1262-0a62-423e-a52e-0f90f7c09ec8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, you use `--treenode-filter` to filter tests. To filter by class name, the syntax would be:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nWait, but the user asked about `dotnet test`. Let me check - TUnit 0.6.x uses MTP. With `dotnet test` and MTP, the filter passing mechanism differs.\n\n\nActually, with newer versions of `dotnet test` (especially .NET 9+), it can work with MTP projects. Since TUnit uses MTP natively, I can pass the filter through using the `--` separator to forward it to the platform:\n\n```\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nThis should work, though the recommended approach is typically `dotnet run` with the filter flag.","outputTokens":487,"requestId":"1BC8:49329:4D04C8:57BA9E:6A03D687"},"id":"81de188a-25e0-4fc5-bd31-570962e17a5e","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:40:37.091Z","parentId":"2c5cde6f-e8f3-4011-aa27-96eeb886ef2f"}
